# Performance Cursor Rules

## Core Web Vitals
- LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) < 2.5s: Optimize images, fonts, critical CSS
- INP (Interaction to Next Paint) < 200ms: Minimize main thread blocking
- CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) < 0.1: Set dimensions on media, use font-display

## JavaScript Performance
- Code split routes and heavy components with dynamic imports
- Use `requestIdleCallback` for non-critical work
- Debounce/throttle event handlers (scroll, resize, input)
- Use Web Workers for CPU-intensive computation
- Avoid memory leaks: clean up event listeners, intervals, subscriptions

## Image Optimization
- Use `next/image`, `<picture>`, or CDN for automatic optimization
- Use WebP/AVIF formats with fallbacks
- Implement lazy loading: `loading="lazy"` for below-fold images
- Set explicit `width` and `height` to prevent CLS
- Use responsive images with `srcset` and `sizes`

## CSS Performance
- Minimize CSS-in-JS runtime overhead — prefer static styles
- Use `content-visibility: auto` for off-screen content
- Avoid layout thrashing: batch DOM reads and writes
- Use `will-change` sparingly for animation optimization

## Caching Strategy
- Use appropriate `Cache-Control` headers for each resource type
- Static assets: `Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable`
- API responses: `Cache-Control: private, max-age=60` (or `stale-while-revalidate`)
- Use service workers for offline support and cache-first strategies

## Monitoring
- Use Lighthouse CI for automated performance testing
- Monitor real user metrics (RUM) with web-vitals library
- Set performance budgets and break builds if exceeded
